{\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg1252\cocoartf1404\cocoasubrtf470 {\fonttbl\f0\fnil\fcharset0 Lato-Regular;} {\colortbl;\red255\green255\blue255;} \deftab720 \pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\f0\fs26 \cf0 These Sushi Cards are going to help you learn to create computer programs in \b Scratch \b0 . To do this, you\'92re going to need to have Scratch! \ \ You can either download it and install it on your computer by going to \b dojo.soy/downloadscratch \b0 or use it in your web browser by going to \b dojo.soy/usescratch \b0 . Do one of these two and once you\'92re set up, move on to the next step.}

{\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg1252\cocoartf1404\cocoasubrtf470 {\fonttbl\f0\fnil\fcharset0 Lato-Regular;} {\colortbl;\red255\green255\blue255;} \deftab720 \pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\f0\fs26 \cf0 Time to get coding! Go back to Scratch and click on the Scratch Cat in the \b sprite list \b0 . The cat is now the \b current sprite \b0 .\ \ Go to the \b Events \b0 category in the \b code blocks palette \b0 and choose the \'93when [flag symbol] clicked\'94 event, then drag it onto the \b current sprite panel. \ \
\b0 Then go to \b Looks \b0 in the \b code blocks palette \b0 and choose the \'93say [Hello!] for [2] secs\'94 block and drag it onto the \b current sprite panel \b0 , connecting it to the end of the other block, like this:\ \ Now click the \b Start Program \
\b0 button and watch what \ happens! }

{\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg1252\cocoartf1404\cocoasubrtf470 {\fonttbl\f0\fnil\fcharset0 Lato-Regular;} {\colortbl;\red255\green255\blue255;} {\*\listtable{\list\listtemplateid1\listhybrid{\listlevel\levelnfc23\levelnfcn23\leveljc0\leveljcn0\levelfollow0\levelstartat1\levelspace360\levelindent0{\*\levelmarker \{disc\}}{\leveltext\leveltemplateid1\'01\uc0\u8226 ;}{\levelnumbers;}\fi-360\li720\lin720 }{\listname ;}\listid1} {\list\listtemplateid2\listhybrid{\listlevel\levelnfc23\levelnfcn23\leveljc0\leveljcn0\levelfollow0\levelstartat1\levelspace360\levelindent0{\*\levelmarker \{disc\}}{\leveltext\leveltemplateid101\'01\uc0\u8226 ;}{\levelnumbers;}\fi-360\li720\lin720 }{\listname ;}\listid2}} {\*\listoverridetable{\listoverride\listid1\listoverridecount0\ls1}{\listoverride\listid2\listoverridecount0\ls2}} \deftab720 \pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\f0\fs26 \cf0 There are a few words from that picture that need explaining:\ \pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\b \cf0 \ The Stage \b0 \ This is where your Scratch Programs run. It has\ \pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0 \ls1\ilvl0\cf0 {\listtext \'95 }One or more \b backgrounds \b0 (images on the background of the screen)\ {\listtext \'95 }Any \b code blocks \b0 associated with it (we\'92ll get to this)\ \pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0 \cf0 \ \pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\b \cf0 \ Sprites\ \pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\b0 \cf0 Any object that goes on the stage is a sprite. In Scratch, the sprite is:\ \pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0 \ls2\ilvl0\cf0 {\listtext \'95 }The image on the \b stage \b0 \ {\listtext \'95 }Any alternative \b costumes \b0 (looks) it has\ {\listtext \'95 }Any \b sounds \b0 associated with it\ {\listtext \'95 }Any \b code \b0 \b blocks \b0 associated with it\ \pard\tx560\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0 \cf0 \ The \b current sprite \b0 is the one that\'92s selected in the \b sprite list \b0 .\ \
\b Code Blocks\
\b0 Code in Scratch comes as blocks, that you click together to make programs. You choose blocks from the \b code blocks palette \b0 and drag them into the \b current sprite panel \b0 , then click them together.\ There are 10 categories of blocks, which are colour coded, and you can select each category from the list at the top of the \b code blocks palette.}

{\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg1252\cocoartf1404\cocoasubrtf470 {\fonttbl\f0\fnil\fcharset0 Lato-Regular;} {\colortbl;\red255\green255\blue255;} \deftab720 \pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\f0\fs26 \cf0 Code blocks run from top to bottom, so the order you snap your code together in matters.\ \ In this example, the sprite will \b say \b0 \'93Hello!\'94 before it will \b play \b0 the \i meow \i0 sound.}

{\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg1252\cocoartf1404\cocoasubrtf470 {\fonttbl\f0\fnil\fcharset0 Lato-Regular;} {\colortbl;\red255\green255\blue255;} \pard\tx560\tx1120\tx1680\tx2240\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\f0\fs26 \cf0 These blocks come from the \b Code Blocks Pallet \b0 where they are broken up into different categories. By clicking on the category names, you can see the blocks in that category. Here, the \b motion \b0 category is selected.\ All of the blocks in the selected category are shown in a list. You can pick the one you want, click on it and hold down the mouse button, then just drag it onto the \b current sprite panel \b0 and let go.}

{\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg1252\cocoartf1404\cocoasubrtf470 {\fonttbl\f0\fnil\fcharset0 Lato-Regular;} {\colortbl;\red255\green255\blue255;} \deftab720 \pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\f0\fs26 \cf0 Once the block is in the \b current sprite pane \b0 you can move it around and snap it to other blocks. If you want to see what a block does, you can double-click on it and it will run!\ \ Normally, you want your blocks to run automatically, when something happens. This is why most of your programs will start with a block from the \b events \b0 category. Most often, it will be this one:}

{\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg1252\cocoartf1404\cocoasubrtf470 {\fonttbl\f0\fnil\fcharset0 Lato-Regular;} {\colortbl;\red255\green255\blue255;} \deftab720 \pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\f0\fs26 \cf0 Now save your work! You do this by going to the \b file \b0 menu and clicking \b save. \b0 \ \ Remember to save regularly as you work!\ \ You can also use \b save as \b0 to save a copy of your program with a new name.}

{\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg1252\cocoartf1404\cocoasubrtf470 {\fonttbl\f0\fnil\fcharset0 Lato-Regular;} {\colortbl;\red255\green255\blue255;} \deftab720 \pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\f0\fs26 \cf0 Now you know how to move code around and make things happen, time to try a simple program: Making the Scratch Cat walk in a circle! \ \ Make sure you have the cat selected in the \b sprite list \b0 and then drag these blocks together. You\'92ll find them in \b events \b0 and \b motion \b0 .\ \ Then, click on the green flag above the \b stage \b0 . If you click too many times and the cat walks away, you can drag it back!}

{\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg1252\cocoartf1404\cocoasubrtf470 {\fonttbl\f0\fnil\fcharset0 Lato-Regular;} {\colortbl;\red255\green255\blue255;} \pard\tx560\tx1120\tx1680\tx2240\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\f0\fs26 \cf0 To get a feel for how this actually works, take the \b go to \b0 block from \b motion \b0 and drop it onto your \b sprite panel \b0 . You don\'92t need to connect it to anything.\ \ Next, pick some values for \b x \b0 and \b y \b0 , fill them in, and double \ click on the block. Try different sets of values to see where \ the cat goes! In Scratch \b x \b0 goes from -240 to 240 and \b y \b0 goes \ from -180 to 180.}

{\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg1252\cocoartf1404\cocoasubrtf470 {\fonttbl\f0\fnil\fcharset0 Lato-Regular;} {\colortbl;\red255\green255\blue255;} \pard\tx560\tx1120\tx1680\tx2240\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\f0\fs26 \cf0 Your cat moves back and forwards now, which is pretty cool, but it doesn\'92t move up or down. Also, if you look through the \b motion \b0 blocks, you\'92ll see there are no blocks for \'93up\'94 or \'93down\'94. There are a whole bunch of them related to \b x \b0 and \b y \b0 though\'85}

{\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg1252\cocoartf1404\cocoasubrtf470 {\fonttbl\f0\fnil\fcharset0 Lato-Regular;} {\colortbl;\red255\green255\blue255;} \pard\tx560\tx1120\tx1680\tx2240\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\f0\fs26 \cf0 Now your scratch cat moves, but wouldn\'92t it be more fun to control it with the arrow keys? On this card, you\'92re going learn how to do that!\ \ As you\'92ve probably guessed, you\'92re going to need \b event \b0 and \b motion \b0 blocks again! This time, you\'92re looking for this block:}

{\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg1252\cocoartf1404\cocoasubrtf470 {\fonttbl\f0\fnil\fcharset0 Lato-Regular;} {\colortbl;\red255\green255\blue255;} \pard\tx560\tx1120\tx1680\tx2240\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\f0\fs26 \cf0 The cat moves all over the screen, but imagine this is a game: How do you restart it? You need to get the cat back to its original location when the player starts the game. In Scratch, they start the game by clicking on the green flag, so you need to change the cat\'92s \b x \b0 and \b y \b0 coordinates when that happens.\ \ That\'92s actually pretty easy! The centre of the stage is (0,0) in \b x \b0 and \b y \b0 coordinates. So all you need is an \b event \b0 block for that green flag and the \b go to \b0 block you\'92re already using. Set the \b go to \b0 to (0,0) and then snap it to the flag event block.}

{\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg1252\cocoartf1404\cocoasubrtf470 {\fonttbl\f0\fnil\fcharset0 Lato-Regular;} {\colortbl;\red255\green255\blue255;} \pard\tx560\tx1120\tx1680\tx2240\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\f0\fs26 \cf0 Now you know about \b x \b0 and \b y \b0 coordinates, you can make the cat move up and down! You just need to change its \b y \b0 value. You can update your code like this:}

{\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg1252\cocoartf1404\cocoasubrtf470 {\fonttbl\f0\fnil\fcharset0 Lato-Regular;} {\colortbl;\red255\green255\blue255;} \pard\tx560\tx1120\tx1680\tx2240\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\f0\fs26 \cf0 Nice! Later, you\'92re going to add some code to make the fish move around on its own, without help from the player. Your player will be the shark, trying to catch the fish. \ \ However, it does look a little funny to have that shark swimming backwards. Just like you\'92d usually turn around rather than walking backwards, the shark would turn around rather than swimming that way. Luckily for you, Scratch has a block for this!\ \ The \b point in direction \b0 block lets you pick the direction your sprite is pointing in. You can type in any number, but it comes with the four you\'92ll need most already in there: \b up \b0 , \b down \b0 , \b left \b0 and \b right \b0 . You\'92ll find it in the \b motion \b0 blocks section. Grab it and snap a couple of them into your shark\'92s code, like this:}

{\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg1252\cocoartf1404\cocoasubrtf470 {\fonttbl\f0\fnil\fcharset0 Lato-Regular;} {\colortbl;\red255\green255\blue255;} \pard\tx560\tx1120\tx1680\tx2240\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\f0\fs26 \cf0 If you tried moving the shark around after you added the \'93point in direction\'94 blocks, you might have noticed something a little strange happening. The shark may not be turning quite right!\ \ The problem here is that the shark sprite started,\ as all sprites do, with the \'93all around\'94 \b rotation style \b0 ,\ and what you need it to have is the \b left-right \b0 style.\ \ As usual, there\'92s a block for that and it\'92s in \b motion \b0 ! You just need to update your reset code from Card 3 to set the rotation style, like this:}

{\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg1252\cocoartf1404\cocoasubrtf470 {\fonttbl\f0\fnil\fcharset0 Lato-Regular;} {\colortbl;\red255\green255\blue255;} \pard\tx560\tx1120\tx1680\tx2240\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\f0\fs26 \cf0 Well, that fish just crashed into the side of the \b stage \b0 , and it was moving far too fast for your shark to catch. First, you need to slow it down. That\'92s actually pretty easy, you just need it to wait for a little while after it moves those 10 steps.\ \ There\'92s a \b control \b0 block that can help you here:\ \ You can set how many \b seconds \b0 you want the fish to \ wait. For now, try half a second (0.5). You can test \ out different values later, to see which is the best for \ the game. Remember you can change the number of \ steps too!}

{\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg1252\cocoartf1404\cocoasubrtf470 {\fonttbl\f0\fnil\fcharset0 Lato-Regular;} {\colortbl;\red255\green255\blue255;} \pard\tx560\tx1120\tx1680\tx2240\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\f0\fs26 \cf0 Ok, now it\'92s time to make the fish swim on its own. To do this, you\'92re going to need a new kind of block: a \b control \b0 block. These let you do things a certain number of times, or under certain conditions.\ \ Select your fish sprite and drag a \'93when green flag clicked\'94 \b event \b0 block, a \'93forever\'94 \b control \b0 block and a \'93move 10 steps\'94 \b motion \b0 block into the \b sprite panel \b0 like this:}

{\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg1252\cocoartf1404\cocoasubrtf470 {\fonttbl\f0\fnil\fcharset0 Lato-Regular;} {\colortbl;\red255\green255\blue255;} \pard\tx560\tx1120\tx1680\tx2240\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\f0\fs26 \cf0 You need the \'93pick random\'94 \b operator \b0 block, and you need to plug it into the \'93turn degrees\'94 \b motion \b0 block by clicking and dragging it into the field where you set the number of degrees. You can change the minimum and maximum numbers it will pick, but the default values (1 and 10) are pretty good for this game, so you can just leave them.\ \ Update the fish code to this and then run it by clicking the green flag:}

{\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg1252\cocoartf1404\cocoasubrtf470 {\fonttbl\f0\fnil\fcharset0 Lato-Regular;} {\colortbl;\red255\green255\blue255;} \pard\tx560\tx1120\tx1680\tx2240\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\f0\fs26 \cf0 The shark moves, the fish swims, but they don\'92t interact: If the fish swims right into the shark\'92s mouth, nothing happens. Time to change that!\ \ First, you need to know if the fish is touching the shark. For this, you\'92ll need a \b control \b0 block and a \b sensing \b0 block. \b Sensing \b0 blocks collect information, like where the sprite is, what it\'92s touching, etc. \ \ The \b control \b0 block is an \'93if\'85 then\'94 block and needs to be given a true/false value. The \b sensing \b0 block you\'92re going to use is \'93touching\'85\'94 where you have to pick the sprite name (if you haven\'92t changed it, it\'92ll be Sprite1). From those pointy ends, you can tell it\'92s going to give you the true/false value \'93if\'85 then\'94 needs.\ \ You can add this into the \'93forever\'94 loop on the fish, after the \'93if on edge bounce\'94:}
